  "prompt": "How does the Test Strategy for a software project differ from the Test Plan?",
  "response": "Let me clarify the differences between a Test Strategy and a Test Plan:\n\nTest Strategy:\n- High-level document\n- Defines overall testing approach for the entire project\n- Typically created at the beginning of the project\n- Defines testing scope, objectives, and methodologies\n- Applies to the whole organization or product line\n- Strategic in nature\n- Long-term, more generic document\n- Created by senior test managers\n- Outlines testing principles, techniques, and tools\n- Provides a comprehensive view of testing approach\n\nTest Plan:\n- Detailed, specific document\n- Focuses on a particular project or release\n- Created for a specific software development project\n- Describes specific testing activities, resources, schedule\n- Tactical and operational in nature\n- Short-term, project-specific document\n- Created by project test leads or managers\n- Provides detailed information about:\n  - Test scope\n  - Test deliverables\n  - Test environments\n  - Specific test cases\n  - Defect management process\n  - Roles and responsibilities\n  - Risks and mitigation strategies\n\nKey Differences:\n1. Level of detail\n2. Scope of application\n3. Timeframe\n4. Purpose and focus\n5. Audience and creators\n\nRelationship:\n- Test Strategy typically informs and guides the Test Plan\n- Test Plan implements the broader strategies outlined in the Test Strategy",
